-The gelatinous?

26:41.184 --> 26:42.518
-The... and... and cartilaginous.

26:42.560 --> 26:44.120
You know? Where there's
actual, like, crunch.

26:44.144 --> 26:47.460
This dish, this delicacy
makes no sense in terms

26:47.461 --> 26:50.318
of Western gastronomy at
all because in the West

26:50.319 --> 26:53.820
there's just no concept
of eating something

26:51.569 --> 26:53.820
for the pleasure of its texture.

26:53.862 --> 26:55.864
Mmm. Delicious.

26:55.906 --> 26:56.970
-Really good.

26:56.971 --> 26:58.033
- Mm-hmm.

26:58.075 --> 27:01.245
♪

27:01.287 --> 27:04.664
So you're sort of
single-handedly making

27:04.706 --> 27:07.251
the beautiful argument
that people should

27:07.293 --> 27:10.254
go against their natural
instincts in the West

27:10.296 --> 27:13.882
and... and open up to
what is, really,

27:13.924 --> 27:17.886
an entirely new spectrum
of initially difficult

27:17.928 --> 27:21.848
and extremely nuanced flavors.

27:21.890 --> 27:24.748
I... I just... I think Chinese
is a world's most

27:24.749 --> 27:25.894
underrated cuisine.

27:25.936 --> 27:28.147
Because everyone
loves Chinese food,

27:28.188 --> 27:30.274
but until recently
people, you know,

27:30.316 --> 27:31.956
mainly in the West
thought of Chinese food

27:31.984 --> 27:34.861
as being something very
familiar and good to eat.

27:34.903 --> 27:39.074
But cheap and like, you
know, a bit junky honestly.

27:39.116 --> 27:42.578
And, um, I think that
now people can see

27:42.620 --> 27:44.997
that it has so much
more to offer.

27:46.332 --> 27:48.708
It's got everything
from the most elevated

27:48.750 --> 27:52.942
banquet food, imperial
cooking, hearty peasant food,

27:52.943 --> 27:56.133
street food, Buddhist
vegetarian cooking,

27:56.134 --> 27:57.301
Muslim cooking.

27:57.343 --> 27:59.719
Ethnic minorities with
their own styles.

27:59.761 --> 28:00.905
And so it's really
what you can call

28:00.929 --> 28:02.306
a gastronomic culture.

28:02.348 --> 28:05.559
♪

28:12.358 --> 28:14.734
In the high stress world of
the professional kitchen

28:14.776 --> 28:17.259
the job of the executive
chef is much like

28:17.260 --> 28:18.322
an air-traffic controller.

28:18.364 --> 28:21.575
One misheard order, one
garbled communication

28:21.617 --> 28:23.910
could lead to, well, disaster.

28:23.952 --> 28:25.912
It is with this in mind
that I arrange for Éric

28:25.954 --> 28:27.956
to receive the attentions
of a specialist

28:27.998 --> 28:30.000
in the maintaining
of perfect hearing

28:30.042 --> 28:32.419
and ear-related health.

28:32.461 --> 28:34.547
But the guy's a doctor?

28:34.548 --> 28:38.008
Or he's like, uh, an amateur
- like in the street?

28:34.588 --> 28:38.008
-He's kind of like a doctor.

28:38.050 --> 28:41.761
More of a technician,
a caregiver.

28:41.803 --> 28:44.598
And you could do it
right here in the park

28:44.640 --> 28:45.765
while enjoying your tea.

28:45.807 --> 28:47.767
Who needs a doctor, bro?

28:47.809 --> 28:49.186
- Well, here you go.

28:49.228 --> 28:50.500
My man needs a cleaning.

28:50.501 --> 28:51.771
Yes, yes.

28:53.232 --> 28:54.254
-Yeah, look at him.

28:54.255 --> 28:55.275
-He's laughing.

28:58.820 --> 29:01.781
Enjoy your therapy, you
might wanna put that down.

29:01.823 --> 29:03.783
If he hits the sweet
spot... just relax, dude.

29:03.825 --> 29:06.203
Just keep your head forward.

29:06.245 --> 29:07.787
What is he doing,
it's scrapping?

29:07.829 --> 29:09.789
Well, he has a
number of devices.

29:09.831 --> 29:11.601
- It's a very...
- But he's using those devices

29:11.625 --> 29:12.959
on everybody else here?

29:12.960 --> 29:14.190
Because... No, no, no.

29:14.191 --> 29:17.756
They're thoroughly sanitized
after every customer.

29:21.843 --> 29:22.928
Stay in place.

29:22.929 --> 29:24.012
If you move, you know.

29:24.054 --> 29:25.805
Don't try this at home, folks.

29:25.847 --> 29:27.433
One wrong move to the
right or the left

29:27.474 --> 29:30.394
and the patient could
lose all memory of life

29:30.436 --> 29:31.811
before 1985.

29:31.853 --> 29:33.813
Which if it includes
Kenny Loggins might be

29:33.855 --> 29:36.816
a good deal, but I digress.

29:36.858 --> 29:38.218
Oh, yeah, here comes
the good part.

29:40.028 --> 29:42.822
Oh, yeah, that's a rush, right?

29:42.864 --> 29:46.702
It's like a... The road to
enlightenment right there.

29:46.744 --> 29:47.786
- Oh, now the massage.

29:47.787 --> 29:50.830
- Oh, and you might as well
straighten out Éric's neck

29:48.870 --> 29:50.830
while you're at it.

29:50.872 --> 29:51.998
Don't do that.

29:53.875 --> 29:55.711
Oops, that didn't sound good.

29:55.753 --> 29:56.836
Oh, God, that's funny.

29:56.878 --> 29:57.897
So you ready for
the ass cleaner?

29:57.921 --> 30:01.841
- This guy, I mean...
- They'll be right over.

30:01.883 --> 30:04.844
Same tools as the ear
cleaner, by the way.

30:07.306 --> 30:08.848
♪

30:08.890 --> 30:13.646
"Work harder and you
will be a better man."

30:13.687 --> 30:16.482
As I explained to
Éric, a true artist

30:16.523 --> 30:18.233
must never stop learning.

30:18.275 --> 30:20.277
The Japanese have a
name for this principle

30:20.319 --> 30:23.447
and the intended pursuit of

30:23.448 --> 30:25.678
knowledge and
enlightenment... - "Kaizen."

30:25.679 --> 30:27.867
- [man speaks
Sichuanese Mandarin]

30:27.909 --> 30:30.496
Today we will learn
fish flavored dish.

30:30.537 --> 30:32.474
- Really important.
- So it was with this in mind,

30:32.498 --> 30:35.250
As well as the classic work of Mr.
Rodney Dangerfield,

30:35.292 --> 30:38.086
that I decided to
go back to school.

30:38.128 --> 30:40.880
To make the ultimate
sacrifice for my friend,

30:40.922 --> 30:43.091
to return to that place
of childhood torment...

30:43.133 --> 30:46.345
Stop trying to suck up to
the teacher, I saw that.

30:46.386 --> 30:47.887
Apple polisher.

30:47.929 --> 30:50.745
So that my friend might
learn, might just maybe

30:50.746 --> 30:53.686
better himself and
hopefully bring

30:53.687 --> 30:56.355
some of that knowledge
to the hungry

30:56.356 --> 30:58.565
and the needy people
at Le Bernardin.

30:58.607 --> 30:59.899
You got that, right?

31:01.819 --> 31:03.153
Like a machine, no problem.

31:03.195 --> 31:05.155
- Yeah.
- Okay.

31:05.197 --> 31:08.367
♪

31:11.328 --> 31:14.373
Whoa, doing good.

31:14.414 --> 31:16.100
- It's a little thick.
- It's a little thick.

31:16.124 --> 31:17.230
-Little thick, man.

31:17.231 --> 31:18.335
-Okay.

31:18.377 --> 31:19.961
In order to get to the top

31:20.003 --> 31:21.380
in the harsh, competitive world

31:21.421 --> 31:24.279
of professional cooking,
sometimes you gotta use

31:24.280 --> 31:25.759
sharp elbows.

31:25.801 --> 31:26.926
- More?
- More starch.

31:26.968 --> 31:28.136
More starch.

31:28.178 --> 31:30.114
- Get your own, man.
- It's a cold world out there.

31:30.138 --> 31:33.433
Better he learns it here
than on the street.

31:34.601 --> 31:36.936
Hands up!

31:36.978 --> 31:38.146
I win the prep.

31:38.188 --> 31:41.358
♪

31:41.400 --> 31:43.777
[speaks Sichuanese Mandarin]

31:43.819 --> 31:45.821
The wok is intensely hot.

31:45.863 --> 31:47.155
Things cook quickly in there.

31:47.197 --> 31:50.158
A few seconds too slow
and things swiftly turn

31:50.200 --> 31:52.952
from the sublime
to the ridiculous.

31:54.788 --> 31:57.332
Okay.

31:57.374 --> 31:58.958
Finished.

31:59.000 --> 32:01.127
Et voilá, cheese eater.

32:01.169 --> 32:04.381
♪

32:15.601 --> 32:16.994
- Over cooked.
- Over cooked. A little.

32:17.018 --> 32:17.977
- Only a little.
- Only a little.

32:18.019 --> 32:19.208
Overcooked.

32:19.209 --> 32:20.397
Damn. Damn.

32:21.690 --> 32:24.192
And, uh, what about this guy?

32:35.412 --> 32:36.996
- The same problem.
- The same problem.

32:37.038 --> 32:38.182
- A little overcooked
- A little overcooked

32:38.206 --> 32:40.166
Overcooked. Did you
hear that, Éric?

32:40.208 --> 32:42.168
-Which one is overcooked?

32:42.169 --> 32:44.087
- And you cut the... the
meat -a little thick.

32:44.088 --> 32:45.964
- And you cut the
meat a little thick.

32:47.048 --> 32:49.008
This is Flinstonian knife work.

32:49.050 --> 32:51.010
You're so competitive,
I can't believe it.

32:51.052 --> 32:52.596
Look at that knife work.

32:52.638 --> 32:54.598
Those mushroom are too big.
Look at that,

32:54.640 --> 32:57.016
you throw off the
balance of the dish.

32:57.058 --> 33:00.041
You see here? You feel
the... the consistency

33:00.042 --> 33:01.438
of the... the meat.

33:10.071 --> 33:12.949
Almost everywhere I've
been, it seems there was

33:12.950 --> 33:15.181
a terrifyingly powerful
yet much loved,

33:15.182 --> 33:18.204
alcoholic beverage at the
very center of the culture.

33:18.246 --> 33:21.416
One whose consumption
is rigorously observed

33:21.458 --> 33:23.836
in ritual and tradition.

33:27.088 --> 33:28.924
Whether it's some
sinister moonshine

33:28.966 --> 33:32.469
in a 55-gallon drum in Africa,
or a distilled spirit

33:32.470 --> 33:35.096
in the jungles of
Borneo, the mountains

33:35.097 --> 33:36.702
of the Caucasus,
or a more refined

33:36.703 --> 33:39.893
concoction as here,
you must drink it.

33:43.104 --> 33:47.693
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you Baijiu.

33:47.734 --> 33:50.737
Baijiu has been around
for a very long time

33:50.779 --> 33:52.238
and the Shui Jing
Fang Distillery

33:52.280 --> 33:56.075
has been making this stuff
for over 500 years.

34:00.330 --> 34:04.292
Normally Chinese people
drink premium Baijiu

34:04.334 --> 34:10.089
in the occasion of...
Entertain important guests.

34:10.130 --> 34:15.094
So in China, premium
Baijiu means a lot.

34:15.136 --> 34:17.263
At a business dinner, a banquet,

34:17.304 --> 34:20.766
one can reasonably
expect to drink quite

34:18.931 --> 34:20.766
a lot of the stuff.

34:20.809 --> 34:23.770
Especially when your hosts
are in the business

34:22.143 --> 34:23.770
of making it.

34:23.812 --> 34:27.148
And my French friend
has concerns.

34:27.190 --> 34:30.150
Do you want to
know how we drink?

34:30.193 --> 34:31.485
Yes, of course.

34:31.527 --> 34:33.551
-Yes, that's very important.

34:33.552 --> 34:35.574
- Chinese tradition.

34:35.614 --> 34:38.702
Uh, we start three cups.

34:38.744 --> 34:40.370
So we drink together.

34:40.411 --> 34:45.708
After three cups, everyone
will with each other

34:45.751 --> 34:46.835
-one by one.

34:46.837 --> 34:47.920
- Welcome to China.

34:47.960 --> 34:49.795
Welcome to Sichuan. Drink up.

34:51.339 --> 34:54.132
I have told him what
might be expected of him

34:54.175 --> 34:57.512
and the futility of resisting.

34:57.554 --> 34:59.305
The aroma is very distinctive.

34:59.347 --> 35:00.807
Very, very special.

35:00.849 --> 35:02.517
There will be food, I told him.

35:02.559 --> 35:04.185
- A lot of food.
- And Baijiu.

35:04.227 --> 35:07.940
And one must not, under
any circumstances,

35:07.981 --> 35:11.777
bring shame on our house.

35:11.818 --> 35:14.153
Now the next round
it's one by one?

35:14.195 --> 35:15.614
- Yes.

35:15.615 --> 35:17.032
-So, how does that work?

35:17.074 --> 35:18.157
♪

35:18.199 --> 35:21.160
Oh, no. Oh, I mean, we
may as well get started.

35:21.202 --> 35:23.162
♪

35:25.206 --> 35:27.042
- Thank you very much.
- Hope you enjoy it.

35:27.084 --> 35:28.961
Thank you very much.

35:29.002 --> 35:30.086
- Welcome to Chengdu.

35:30.087 --> 35:31.170
-Thank you so much.

35:31.212 --> 35:34.257
♪

35:41.014 --> 35:44.059
In business, how often do
you entertain like this?

35:44.101 --> 35:47.062
Two... two, three days a week.

35:47.104 --> 35:49.564
- Two, three days.

35:49.606 --> 35:53.359
And sometimes, in one
day three times.

35:53.401 --> 35:55.194
- Oh, three times?
- Yeah.

35:55.236 --> 35:58.657
♪

35:59.699 --> 36:01.451
Oh, wait.

36:01.452 --> 36:03.202
Uh, excuse me, Éric?

36:03.244 --> 36:04.454
Yes, Tony?

36:07.248 --> 36:09.084
Wow.

36:09.126 --> 36:13.005
My dear friend, thank you
so much for taking me here.

36:13.046 --> 36:15.173
I will remember forever.

36:16.716 --> 36:18.010
Okay, good.

36:18.051 --> 36:21.179
♪

37:22.574 --> 37:26.119
♪

37:36.004 --> 37:37.964
Like many residents of
the City of Chengdu,

37:38.006 --> 37:40.299
we decide to head out to the
country for the weekend.

37:40.341 --> 37:42.969
Get in touch with,
like, nature, man.

37:43.011 --> 37:45.680
I made a potentially lethal
mistake this morning.

37:45.722 --> 37:47.682
- I did something I never do.
- Which is?

37:47.724 --> 37:50.560
I ate a Western
breakfast at the hotel.

37:50.602 --> 37:52.311
It's bad... always,
always bad news.

37:52.353 --> 37:54.731
- Why?
- It's just something you shouldn't do

37:54.773 --> 37:56.191
When you're outside
of the States.

37:56.233 --> 37:57.984
Never eat the Western
breakfast in a hotel.

37:58.026 --> 38:00.361
-Now, that I agree, yeah.

38:00.403 --> 38:02.321
- I'm feeling it already.
- It's not good.

38:02.363 --> 38:05.992
Well, the good news, we are
sitting by the bathrooms.

38:06.034 --> 38:07.786
You know, and when,
you know, on a train

38:07.827 --> 38:09.558
-is never a good thing.

38:09.559 --> 38:11.289
- You have luxury
taste, I noticed.

38:14.042 --> 38:15.815
-Kind of elitist taste.

38:15.816 --> 38:17.587
- Really?

38:17.629 --> 38:20.590
I don't like to roll in my
own... in a moving bathroom,

38:20.591 --> 38:22.175
that's elitist?

38:25.804 --> 38:29.307
Embrace... the experience.

38:31.059 --> 38:34.229
♪

38:35.814 --> 38:38.942
We're about maybe
115 kilometers away

38:38.984 --> 38:41.360
from the center of...
City of Chengdu.

38:41.402 --> 38:43.362
♪

38:43.404 --> 38:45.364
Chen Zhong is a
filmmaker from Beijing

38:45.406 --> 38:48.952
who often returns to Chengdu,
the place of his birth,

38:48.994 --> 38:51.746
to enjoy the more
laid-back pace.

38:51.788 --> 38:56.481
So on the weekends...
everybody comes out to...

38:56.482 --> 38:58.170
What's it called?

38:58.211 --> 39:00.421
Alongdaloo. It's a...
It's a term to describe

39:00.463 --> 39:01.840
a place like this.

39:01.881 --> 39:03.549
- Right.

39:03.550 --> 39:05.177
- It means, you know,
the... the, uh,

39:05.218 --> 39:08.387
agricultural family
happiness some say.

39:08.429 --> 39:09.657
"Agricultural family happiness."

